  "footnotes": [
    "Attila's court (c.445–453): Attila's capital was located on the Great Plain near the Tisza River; his court received Roman ambassadors (Priscus' account is the main source); after Attila's death the Hunnic confederation collapsed almost immediately, the defeated Germanic tribes rising in revolt at the Battle of Nedao (454)",
    "Gepid Kingdom (454–567): the Gepids, a Germanic people, established a kingdom in the Tisza/Transylvania region after the collapse of Hunnic power; they were destroyed by the Lombard-Avar alliance in 567; the Lombards then vacated Pannonia for Italy in 568, leaving it to the Avars",
    "Avar Khaganate (568–804): the Avars held the Carpathian Basin for 236 years, conducting devastating raids into Byzantium and Frankish territories; Charlemagne's campaigns of 791–796 destroyed the Avar 'Ring' (a circular fortified capital of legendary wealth) and ended the Avar state",
    "Battle of Mohács (1526): the decisive Ottoman victory over Louis II of Hungary (who drowned fleeing) ended the unified medieval kingdom; Hungary was then divided three ways — Ottoman-occupied center, Habsburg 'Royal Hungary' in the northwest, and the Principality of Transylvania as an Ottoman vassal in the east — a division lasting 173 years",
    "Treaty of Trianon (1920): Hungary lost 72% of its territory and 64% of its population; Transylvania went to Romania, Slovakia to Czechoslovakia, Croatia-Slavonia to Yugoslavia; the trauma of Trianon remains the central wound of Hungarian national memory and continues to shape Hungarian politics",
    "Hungarian Revolution 1956: a nationwide uprising against Soviet-backed rule began on 23 October 1956; revolutionary councils briefly took control of the country; Soviet forces invaded on 4 November, crushing the revolution and killing an estimated 2,500 Hungarians; 200,000 fled as refugees"
  ]
